-# Microsoft Intune Best-Practice Guide
-
-Enterprise guidance for a 5k-50k device environment with hybrid AD history, a move toward cloud-only management, and a strong preference for scalable, repeatable operations.
+# Intune Best Practices Guide
 
-Last validated against Microsoft Learn guidance: 2026-03-19.
+_Current as of March 19, 2026_
 
 ## Executive Summary
-
-The most reliable Intune operating model at this scale is cloud-first, phased, and opinionated. Use Intune as the primary control plane for device configuration, compliance, app delivery, and security integration. Keep Conditional Access, update rings, and app deployment tightly aligned so that identity, posture, and servicing behave as one system.
-
-For a hybrid estate moving to cloud-only, do not treat migration as a single cutover. Inventory dependencies first, then move new devices to Entra join and Autopilot, and retire legacy management in waves. Co-management is a transition pattern, not an end state, unless there is a durable technical reason to keep Configuration Manager in place.
-
-The highest-value outcomes are:
-
-- Fewer management planes and fewer conflicting policies.
-- Faster onboarding through Autopilot and standardized enrollment paths.
-- Better security through compliance, Conditional Access, and endpoint protection.
-- Lower support load through predictable rings, packaging standards, and cleanup discipline.
-
-## Audience, Scope, and Assumptions
-
-This guide is written for endpoint engineering, identity, security, and support teams that operate a large enterprise tenant. It assumes:
-
-- A Windows-heavy fleet with some macOS, mobile, shared, and specialty devices.
-- A history of on-prem Active Directory, Group Policy, and possibly Configuration Manager.
-- A target state that favors cloud-native management, even if the current state does not.
-- Multiple device personas, including corporate-owned, BYOD, frontline, kiosk, and task-specific devices.
-
-The guidance intentionally distinguishes between device classes. A single policy model rarely works across all personas, and frontline or shared devices usually need separate enrollment, access, app, and compliance decisions.
-
-## Operating Principles
-
-Use these principles as the default design rules for the environment:
-
-1. Prefer one owner per control. If Intune owns a setting, do not also let GPO or Configuration Manager silently override it.
-2. Enforce in phases. Validate in report-only or pilot rings before broad production rollout.
-3. Measure everything. Treat enrollment success, compliance rate, deployment success, patch latency, and support volume as operational KPIs.
-4. Limit exceptions. Exceptions should be time-bound, owned, and reviewed.
-5. Design for clarity. Naming, scope tags, groups, and filters should make the environment easier to operate, not more expressive.
-6. Protect user experience. A secure design that blocks routine work without a recovery path will be bypassed.
-
-## Licensing and Capability Planning
 
-Licensing should drive architecture, not just procurement. Start with the capabilities you need, then map them to the smallest set of SKUs that supports the design.
-
-| Need | Typical Licensing Consideration | Notes |
-| --- | --- | --- |
-| Core MDM/MAM | Intune Plan 1 | Baseline for device management and app protection. |
-| Conditional Access and many identity controls | Microsoft Entra ID P1 or P2 | P2 is often needed where risk-based controls or more advanced governance are in scope. |
-| Endpoint security integration | Microsoft Defender for Endpoint | Commonly paired with Intune for posture and risk signals. |
-| Shared device or kiosk scenarios | Device-only or appropriate user licensing | Match licensing to the ownership model. |
-| Remote support | Intune Suite add-on such as Remote Help | Useful where support at scale needs secure assisted remediation. |
-| Privilege elevation | Intune Suite add-on such as Endpoint Privilege Management | Strong fit when removing standing admin rights is a goal. |
-| Certificate lifecycle simplification | Intune Suite add-on such as Cloud PKI | Best when certificate operations are a pain point. |
-| Standardizing third-party app delivery | Intune Suite add-on such as Enterprise App Management | Good fit for large app portfolios with many common ISVs. |
-| Secure private app access for unmanaged devices | Tunnel for MAM | Use when app-level access is enough and enrollment is not desired. |
-
-Treat Intune Suite as a targeted investment. Add it where a concrete operational or security use case exists, not as a default purchase for every tenant.
-
-## Tenant Hygiene and Governance
-
-Scale depends on administrative clarity. Keep tenant objects predictable, delegated, and easy to audit.
-
-Recommended practices:
-
-- Standardize naming for policies, profiles, apps, groups, and filters.
-- Use RBAC and scope tags to constrain administrative blast radius.
-- Keep dynamic groups and assignment filters intentionally small and test them before production use.
-- Establish lifecycle rules for policy versioning, review, retirement, and owner reassignment.
-- Keep exceptions visible and documented so they do not become hidden architecture.
-
-Avoid these patterns:
-
-- Broad admin visibility by default.
-- Unbounded dynamic group sprawl.
-- Policies with no owner or no retirement path.
-- Reliance on the default scope tag for everything.
+Treat Microsoft Intune as an operating model, not a one-time migration. In large enterprise environments, success depends on a deliberate sequence: inventory devices, apps, policies, identity dependencies, and support readiness; define the target state; then roll out in phases. Microsoft’s guidance continues to favor assessment, staged deployment, and service desk readiness as the safest path to broad adoption.
 
-## Hybrid-to-Cloud Transition Strategy
+The most common failure mode in large tenants is unmanaged complexity: overlapping policies, duplicated settings across policy types, inconsistent targeting, and rushed Conditional Access enforcement. A healthy Intune program separates identity, device management, app delivery, and access control into clear ownership boundaries.
 
-Move from hybrid to cloud in waves, not by declaration.
+Windows 10 should now be treated as exception inventory with either commercial ESU coverage or an explicit exit plan. It is out of support unless the device is on an ESU path, and it should not be managed as a steady-state platform.
 
-### Recommended sequence
+Co-management is best treated as a transition pattern for hybrid estates, not the default end state. Intune-only remains the preferred target for greenfield environments and for organizations that no longer need Configuration Manager for durable workloads.
 
-1. Inventory the current state.
-2. Identify dependencies on GPO, Configuration Manager, PKI, local scripts, and on-prem authentication.
-3. Build a target state for new devices using Entra join, Autopilot, and Intune-first policy design.
-4. Move pilot populations first, then expand by persona, platform, and business unit.
-5. Retire legacy settings and management planes after the new path is stable.
+Intune Suite capabilities should be evaluated by use case. Some advanced capabilities are available as standalone add-ons, while others require Intune Plan 2 or the Suite. None of them should be assumed as baseline requirements for every tenant.
 
-### What to inventory first
+## Quick-Start Checklist
 
-- Device join state and enrollment method.
-- Applications that depend on on-prem services.
-- Certificate, Wi-Fi, VPN, and auth dependencies.
-- Group Policy settings with no Intune equivalent yet.
-- Configuration Manager workloads that still matter.
+Use this checklist before broad rollout.
 
-### Migration rule
+- Define ownership boundaries for corporate-owned, shared, frontline, and BYOD devices.
+- Confirm licensing for Intune and the Entra ID features required for automatic enrollment and Conditional Access.
+- Decide whether the initial target is Intune-only, co-managed, or a staged transition from hybrid.
+- Establish a naming standard for tenants, policies, profiles, apps, and rings.
+- Set MDM user scope deliberately and test it in a pilot group before expanding.
+- Define enrollment restrictions early so unsupported device types do not enter the tenant.
+- Build pilot rings for each major workload: enrollment, compliance, CA, apps, updates, and security baselines.
+- Treat Windows 10 as exception inventory with ESU coverage or a retirement plan.
+- Create a policy conflict review process before adding security baselines or endpoint security policies.
+- Train the service desk before enabling enforcement that can affect access or enrollment.
+- Configure break-glass exclusions for Conditional Access and validate them.
+- Decide where assignment filters will replace group sprawl.
+- Select your reporting model up front: compliance, enrollment, updates, apps, and endpoint health.
+- Define a cleanup strategy for stale devices, Autopilot records, and identity records.
 
-Do not migrate devices until the app, identity, and PKI dependencies for that population are understood. Most failed migrations are dependency failures, not enrollment failures.
+## Common Anti-Patterns
 
-## Identity Foundation and Access Alignment
+Avoid these patterns in enterprise tenants.
 
-Identity is the decision point for Zero Trust. Device management only works when access policy and device posture agree.
+| Anti-pattern | Why it causes problems | Better approach |
+|---|---|---|
+| Overlapping baselines and duplicate settings across policy types | Conflicts are hard to diagnose and can create inconsistent results | Assign one owner for each setting and maintain a settings ownership matrix |
+| Relying on many nearly identical Entra groups | Creates churn and makes targeting harder to maintain | Reuse groups and use assignment filters for narrow targeting |
+| Turning on broad Conditional Access before app protection or compliance is ready | Can block users before the required controls are in place | Use report-only mode, pilot rings, and phased enforcement |
+| Treating Windows 10 as a standard operating platform | Windows 10 is out of support unless covered by ESU | Track Windows 10 separately and assign an explicit exit plan or ESU coverage |
+| Treating cleanup rules as endpoint remediation | Cleanup rules hide records; they do not secure or remove the device | Use retire, wipe, or delete for lifecycle actions |
+| Keeping co-management indefinitely without a decision owner | Splits operational ownership and slows cloud adoption | Treat co-management as a transition path unless a durable dependency remains |
+| Buying Intune Suite add-ons without a use case | Adds cost without operational value | Map each capability to a clear business or support requirement |
 
-Recommended approach:
+## Tenant Hygiene
 
-- Prefer Entra join for new corporate Windows devices.
-- Prefer Password Hash Sync over Pass-through Authentication where possible, unless a specific dependency blocks it.
-- Use Conditional Access for MFA and device-based access requirements.
-- Use passwordless methods for mature user populations.
-- Keep break-glass accounts outside routine policies, but monitor and test them regularly.
+A healthy tenant is easier to govern, troubleshoot, and audit.
 
-### Decision framework: Entra join vs. Hybrid join
+Use RBAC and scope tags to divide administration by geography, business unit, or function. Keep naming standards consistent for policies, apps, profiles, groups, and rings so operators can identify ownership quickly. Exclude emergency accounts from Conditional Access and maintain documented break-glass procedures.
 
-| Use Entra Join When | Use Hybrid Join When |
-| --- | --- |
-| New corporate device builds are the norm. | A legacy app or auth dependency still requires domain join behavior. |
-| Cloud-first management is the goal. | Migration risk is still too high for a full identity cutover. |
-| Conditional Access and Autopilot are central. | The device must remain tightly coupled to on-prem processes for now. |
+Prefer built-in virtual grouping patterns and assignment filters where possible. Reserve custom Entra groups for durable business boundaries such as country, legal entity, or device class. Avoid group nesting and highly dynamic group structures unless there is a clear operational reason.
 
-Hybrid join should be treated as temporary technical debt unless there is a clear business reason to keep it.
+Use a settings ownership matrix for device configuration, security baselines, compliance, and endpoint security. That single artifact prevents the most common form of tenant drift: two teams configuring the same setting in different places.
 
 ## Enrollment Strategy
 
-Design enrollment by ownership and use case, not by convenience.
+Enrollment should follow ownership and management intent. One enrollment pattern rarely fits every scenario.
 
-| Device Type | Preferred Pattern | Notes |
-| --- | --- | --- |
-| Corporate Windows | Autopilot + automatic enrollment | Best for standard managed endpoints. |
-| BYOD | App protection without full enrollment when possible | Keep user privacy and reduce friction where full management is unnecessary. |
-| Shared or kiosk Windows | Purpose-built shared-device or kiosk flow | Avoid user-centric assumptions. |
-| Frontline | Low-friction, role-specific enrollment and app set | Optimize for shift work and quick access. |
-| Specialty devices | Separate handling and exception process | Do not force the standard model onto labs, VDI, or task-specific endpoints. |
+| Scenario | Recommended path | Notes |
+|---|---|---|
+| New corporate Windows devices | Windows Autopilot | Best fit for standard cloud-first provisioning |
+| Legacy domain-joined Windows devices | Co-management or GPO-based auto-enrollment | Useful during transition from hybrid management |
+| BYOD where full device management is not required | App protection and MAM | Avoid unnecessary full MDM enrollment |
+| Shared or frontline devices | Purpose-built enrollment flow | Validate restrictions, shared use, and user experience separately |
+| Education devices | Intune for Education, if the school use case fits | Use as a special-case edge path, not a default enterprise pattern |
 
-Avoid forcing full MDM on a device that only needs app protection. That creates support load without adding meaningful control.
+For Windows automatic enrollment, scope matters. Set the MDM user scope deliberately and validate the pilot before expanding. Automatic enrollment depends on the right licensing and identity configuration, so do not treat it as a default-on control.
 
-## Device Configuration and Policy Design
+Enrollment restrictions are applied to user-driven enrollments. They do not apply the same way to non-user-driven scenarios, so design those paths separately instead of relying on the standard restriction model.
 
-Build a layered policy model:
+Key scenarios that use the default policy because they are not user-driven include:
 
-- Use Settings Catalog and security baselines as the starting point.
-- Reserve custom profiles for gaps or clearly defined exceptions.
-- Keep a single owner for each major setting or control area.
-- Use Group Policy analytics to retire legacy settings where possible.
+- Windows Autopilot self-deploying mode
+- Windows Autopilot pre-provisioned deployment
+- Co-managed enrollments
+- Azure Virtual Desktop
+- Windows 365
+- Userless Apple automated device enrollment
+- Android Enterprise corporate-owned dedicated devices
+- Bulk enrollment via Windows Configuration Designer
 
-### Recommended layering
+Shared and frontline estates need platform-specific design, not generic enrollment guidance.
 
-1. Baseline security and configuration profiles.
-2. Workload-specific policy layers.
-3. Persona-specific exceptions.
-4. Time-bound temporary exceptions where absolutely necessary.
+| Platform | Recommended shared pattern | Notes |
+|---|---|---|
+| Android | Android Enterprise dedicated devices, optionally with Microsoft Entra shared device mode | Good for kiosks, logistics, inventory, and task devices |
+| iOS/iPadOS | Shared iPad or Microsoft Entra shared device mode, depending on device type | Shared iPad is preferred for iPad-based shared use |
+| Windows | Shared PC, multi-user, or frontline worker patterns | Match the pattern to whether the device is shared or user-associated |
 
-### Common failure mode
+For Windows frontline devices, separate shared devices from user-associated devices. Shared PCs and multi-user scenarios are different from one-user frontline laptops and should be managed differently.
 
-The same setting is configured in GPO, Intune, and Configuration Manager at once. That creates non-deterministic behavior and makes troubleshooting unnecessarily expensive.
+## App Lifecycle and Win32 Packaging
 
-## Compliance Policies and Access Enforcement
+Win32 app management works best when packaging is standardized.
 
-Compliance is the device posture signal that Conditional Access consumes. Do not enable access enforcement before the compliance model is ready.
+Use explicit detection rules, consistent install and uninstall commands, and clear versioning. Do not assume supersedence will automatically replace an older package unless you have explicitly targeted the new app and tested the relationship. Keep dependency chains shallow because deep graphs are harder to support and can create deployment conflicts.
 
-Recommended practices:
-
-- Define compliance policies before enforcing compliant-device access.
-- Set tenant compliance defaults so “no policy assigned” does not mean “trusted.”
-- Use grace periods deliberately and document them.
-- Integrate Defender for Endpoint or mobile threat defense signals where they add value.
-
-### Decision framework: compliance to access
+Enterprise App Catalog content is useful for accelerating deployment, but defaults should still be validated. If you override install or uninstall behavior, test the package end to end before production rollout.
 
-1. Decide which apps require device trust.
-2. Define the minimum compliance state for those apps.
-3. Create and test the compliance policy.
-4. Validate Conditional Access in report-only mode.
-5. Enforce only after the policy works at pilot scale.
+For large tenants, maintain a packaging standard that defines:
 
-If you enforce Conditional Access before the compliance model exists, you risk creating a lockout path for the very devices you are trying to manage.
+- Installer source and version control
+- Detection logic
+- Return codes and retry behavior
+- Content delivery model
+- Supersedence and rollback rules
+- Support ownership
 
-## App Lifecycle and Win32 Packaging
+## Update Rings and Feature Updates
 
-At scale, app reliability is operational strategy.
+Update rings and feature update policies serve different purposes. Rings shape client behavior and cadence. Feature update policies control the target OS release more directly.
 
-Recommended practices:
+Use rings to define pilot, broad, and production populations. Use feature update policies to move devices to a specific release on a schedule. Do not let deferral settings silently delay a broader migration plan.
 
-- Prefer Win32 for complex desktop apps.
-- Standardize packaging, detection, uninstall, dependencies, and supersedence.
-- Use Delivery Optimization where it makes sense for bandwidth and scale.
-- Separate packaging ownership from app approval ownership.
-- Use installation deadlines and restart behavior intentionally.
+If Windows Autopatch is in use, do not assign custom update rings to Autopatch-managed devices unless those devices are intentionally managed outside Autopatch. The service expects its own rollout sequencing, and duplicate ownership creates confusing restart and deferral behavior.
 
-### Packaging standards
+Autopatch groups should still follow staged deployment discipline. The service expects at least two rings for gradual rollout, with Test and Last as the minimum default structure.
 
-- One package per versioned app baseline.
-- Deterministic detection logic.
-- Explicit uninstall behavior.
-- Documented dependencies and supersedence.
+## Security Baselines
 
-### Common failure mode
+Security baselines are starting points, not immutable standards. Use them to establish a recommended foundation, then adjust only where business risk, device type, or operational reality requires it.
 
-Treating packaging as a one-off task. That creates inconsistent detection logic, hidden dependencies, and weak uninstall paths.
+Conflicts are the main risk. Avoid deploying multiple baselines or overlapping endpoint security and device configuration policies that control the same setting on the same device set. Review exceptions explicitly instead of hiding them in unrelated profiles.
 
-## Update Rings and Feature Update Management
+Defender baselines should be validated carefully in virtual desktop or VM environments. Baseline applicability differs by platform, and physical-device hardening is not always appropriate for virtualized estates.
 
-Windows servicing is a lifecycle control, not just a patch task.
+Before adopting a baseline in production, verify:
 
-Recommended practices:
+- Platform applicability
+- Conflicting policies
+- Local admin and support impact
+- Exception handling
+- Monitoring and rollback path
 
-- Maintain pilot and production rings.
-- Separate quality updates, feature updates, and driver or firmware strategy.
-- Use Autopatch where it fits the tenant and operating model.
-- Define rollback and pause procedures before production rollout.
+## Compliance Policies
 
-### Ring model
+Compliance policies should support access decisions, not become a catch-all configuration tool.
 
-| Ring | Purpose | Typical Population |
-| --- | --- | --- |
-| Pilot | Validate behavior and catch issues early | IT, power users, and controlled test groups |
-| Broad | Standard production servicing | Most corporate endpoints |
-| Holdback / exception | Isolate problem devices or business-critical constraints | Limited exception set |
+If Conditional Access depends on compliance, set devices with no assigned compliance policy to Not compliant. That prevents unmanaged or not-yet-assigned devices from being treated as trusted. Define the compliance status validity period deliberately so stale devices do not remain trusted too long and new failures do not create unnecessary access loss.
 
-Do not run the entire fleet on one ring. That eliminates your ability to see failures before they become outages.
+Keep compliance focused on measurable signals that map directly to access control. Do not overload compliance with settings that belong in device configuration, endpoint security, or remediation workflows.
 
-## Device Lifecycle and Cleanup
+A good compliance policy answers a narrow question: should this device be trusted for access right now?
 
-Device inventory must stay accurate or targeting and reporting will drift.
+## Conditional Access Alignment
 
-Recommended practices:
+Conditional Access should reflect the device and app model, not force every user into the same control path.
 
-- Define retire, wipe, delete, and deregister criteria.
-- Align offboarding with HR and asset management.
-- Clean stale objects on a schedule.
-- Preserve recovery data and retirement dependencies before device disposal or reassignment.
+Use device compliance for managed endpoints. Use app protection policies for BYOD and MAM scenarios when the device should remain unenrolled. App-based Conditional Access is the right fit for supported mobile MAM scenarios, and on Windows it is narrower, primarily centered on Microsoft Edge and Windows MAM support.
 
-### Lifecycle rule
+Deploy Conditional Access in report-only mode first, then validate pilot impact before enforcing. At least one emergency access or break-glass account should be excluded from all Conditional Access policies. That account should be tested, documented, and operationally protected.
 
-Retire the device in the management system before or alongside physical disposal, and remove stale records only after you are sure they are no longer needed for compliance, audit, or re-enrollment.
+Use this rollout pattern:
 
-## Reporting, Monitoring, and Operational Readiness
+- Start in report-only
+- Pilot with a small, representative user set
+- Review sign-in logs and policy impact
+- Fix app protection and compliance dependencies
+- Enforce only after the control path is stable
 
-Use the right level of telemetry for the job.
+## Device Lifecycle and Cleanup
 
-- Operational reports: fix the problem now.
-- Organizational reports: show health and trend.
-- Historical data: identify drift and capacity needs.
-- Azure Monitor or Log Analytics: build custom operational views when built-in reporting is not enough.
+Separate operational actions from inventory cleanup.
 
-Recommended KPIs:
+Retire, wipe, and delete are distinct actions. Cleanup rules hide stale devices from Intune views and reports after an inactivity window; they do not wipe the device, retire the device, or remove the Microsoft Entra ID object. For offboarding, confirm how the device affects Intune, Autopilot, and Entra ID records so you do not leave orphaned objects behind.
 
-- Enrollment success rate.
-- Compliance rate.
-- App deployment success rate.
-- Update latency by ring.
-- Support tickets tied to policy changes.
+Pair cleanup rules with certificate expiry, re-enrollment planning, or offboarding workflows. Otherwise, stale records may disappear from reporting while the underlying identity objects remain active.
 
-Endpoint Analytics and co-management dashboards can help when used as operating tools, not as passive dashboards.
+Use the right action for the outcome you want:
 
-## Co-Management vs Intune-Only Decision Framework
+- Retire for managed removal of corporate data and MDM state
+- Wipe for full reset when device reuse is not desired
+- Delete for record cleanup when the device is already handled elsewhere
+- Cleanup rules only for aging out stale inventory
 
-Use co-management when you still have real Configuration Manager value and real legacy dependencies. Move to Intune-only when the cloud path is ready and the operational benefit is clear.
+## Reporting and Monitoring
 
-### Decision table
+Use layered reporting. No single dashboard answers every operational question.
 
-| Choose Co-Management When | Choose Intune-Only When |
-| --- | --- |
-| Configuration Manager still owns important workloads. | Identity, enrollment, apps, updates, and access are cloud-ready. |
-| Legacy dependencies are still being removed. | New device builds are cloud-native by default. |
-| You need a phased migration path with minimal disruption. | The support model is simpler with a single control plane. |
-| You need to shift workloads one at a time. | The value of dual management no longer outweighs the complexity. |
+At minimum, build reporting around enrollment, compliance, updates, app deployment, and endpoint health. For large tenants, segment reports by region, business unit, or device class so local issues do not disappear into aggregate averages.
 
-### Co-management rules
+Advanced Analytics is most valuable when you need device-level and fleet-level signals that help your support organization act early. It is only effective if there is an operational process to review the data and respond.
 
-- Move one workload at a time.
-- Pilot every workload change.
-- Define a retirement path for each legacy dependency.
-- Do not leave workloads split indefinitely without a plan.
+A practical reporting model includes:
 
-Intune-only is the preferred end state for most modern enterprises. Co-management is the bridge, not the destination.
+- Fleet health for operations
+- Compliance and access for security
+- Enrollment and app success for service desk
+- Update posture for patching teams
+- Exception tracking for governance
 
-## Security Integrations and Endpoint Protection
+## Co-Management vs Intune-Only
 
-Security and endpoint management should share telemetry and enforcement loops.
+Co-management is a transition path for hybrid estates. Intune-only is the preferred end state when Configuration Manager no longer provides a durable operational benefit.
 
-Recommended practices:
+Use co-management when you need to move workloads gradually, validate policy behavior in stages, or preserve legacy app delivery and task sequence dependencies during transition. Move one workload at a time, pilot it, then promote it. Do not switch multiple workloads simultaneously unless you can absorb the troubleshooting cost.
 
-- Configure antivirus, firewall, disk encryption, ASR, EDR, and account protection policies.
-- Integrate Microsoft Defender for Endpoint where risk and compliance need to inform each other.
-- Use Endpoint Privilege Management to remove standing admin rights where the license and maturity justify it.
-- Use Remote Help with RBAC and audit expectations if support needs secure remote assistance.
-- Use Cloud PKI when certificate operations are a meaningful operational burden.
+Use Intune-only when the environment is greenfield or when cloud management fully meets the workload requirements. Keep co-management only when there is a real dependency on Configuration Manager, not because the old model is familiar.
 
-### Intune Suite decision rule
+Decision guidance:
 
-Only adopt a Suite capability when it reduces measurable friction, risk, or operating cost. If a feature has no clear owner or no measurable problem to solve, delay it.
+| Question | If yes | If no |
+|---|---|---|
+| Do you still depend on ConfigMgr for a durable workload? | Keep co-management for that workload | Move to Intune-only |
+| Do you need staged migration with workload-by-workload control? | Co-management is appropriate | Intune-only is simpler |
+| Is the environment greenfield? | Intune-only is usually the default | Consider co-management only if a legacy dependency exists |
+| Are users experiencing duplicate ownership and confusion? | Reduce overlap and accelerate cloud cutover | Maintain current split only if justified |
 
-## Shared Devices, Frontline, and Specialty Workloads
+## Licensing: E3, E5, Plan 2, and Intune Suite
 
-Shared and specialty endpoints require different assumptions.
+Base your licensing model on the management capabilities you actually need. Core device management is typically covered through Intune Plan 1 entitlements in broader Microsoft suites. Intune Plan 2 and Intune Suite add advanced endpoint management capabilities, but they are not the same thing as every optional add-on.
 
-Recommended practices:
+Some capabilities are available as standalone add-ons, while others are only available with Intune Plan 2 or Intune Suite. Review the Intune add-ons blade in your tenant before making assumptions about packaging.
 
-- Use shared-device modes or dedicated device patterns where supported.
-- Prefer device-assigned apps and policies for userless or shared devices.
-- Keep session length, sign-in behavior, and app access aligned with the use case.
-- Treat labs, VDI, and task-specific devices as separate design categories.
+Common advanced capabilities to evaluate include:
 
